WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Mark Sellors, Head of Data Engineering, Mango Solutions

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Mark Sellors, Head of Data Engineering, Mango Solutions

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
R is a one-word trick that we use to get R into production.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I'm also not going to talk specifically about any code that might help you run R in production.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.000
That's not really the area that I work in.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So where I work, a lot of the time we're helping organisations adopt the R language

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and trying to help businesses of varying sizes, from very small organisations

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
up to massive government agencies to adopt the language in their businesses,

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
which isn't always an easy conversation to have.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
So this is kind of my starting point.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:21.000
I genuinely think that all of the technical barriers to running R in production are easy to overcome.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
I say easy, I mean comparatively easy, right?

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Those are always challenges.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
But it's the cultural barriers that slow us down.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
So there's some overlap here with what Joe Cheng was talking about this morning.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
I like to present this as a kind of inspirational quote,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
but actually it was just something I said on Twitter one time.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
But I do genuinely believe it.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:53.000
So much like Joe, who kind of, you know, stealing my thunder this morning,

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
we need to start out with a working definition of what production actually means.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And mine's kind of similar to Joe, there's a lot of overlap.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
But basically, when people say production,

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
they tend to sort of have this idea in their head of what production means.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
And production is the same as massive, right?

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
That's kind of the basis for all these production kind of conversations.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
And when people historically have said, oh, well, you know, you can't run R in production,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.000
quite often what they mean is you can't run R at scale.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
And even that's not true anymore.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So these are, I'm not 100% sure because I stole the image from Google,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
but I think these are Google racks, actually, in their data center.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And I think they're Google's tensor processing units.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
But this is the kind of thing that people think of when we talk about production.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
But actually, production and scale, not the same thing at all.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
So for me, production is anything that's run repeatedly,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.000
and that the business relies on.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
So hopefully, I'm kind of lining up with Joe Chang on that one.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And the important bits of that are that it's repeated or continuous,

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
kind of an extension of the same idea, and that it's relied upon.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Now, in most of the organizations that I work with,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
when you're implementing R in production,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
the people, the kind of target audience for those R environments

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
are anywhere from 10, 20 people up to a few hundred people.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
So those people will rely on the information that's being presented to them,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
whether it's information in a Shiny application,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
or whether they're running R on a HPC cluster, or something like that.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
They're actually relying on that information that they're getting back

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
to kind of inform decision-making within the business,

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
or to bring a new drug to market, or whatever it may be.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
So actually, R is great in production.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
There are a number of reasons for this.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
R doesn't have a lot of the baggage that other programming languages do.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.000
And I'm thinking specifically things like the Python 2.3 schism.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
There's still an awful lot of stuff in Python 2,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
which is slowing adoption of Python 3.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
And that's because it's used so heavily on Linux systems

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
where vendors are perhaps a little slower to upgrade things.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Obviously, R doesn't have that baggage,

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
so you can install whatever version or versions of R you want to use.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And I've found overall that performance is exceptional.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
On top of that, you've obviously got a fantastic package ecosystem

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
and things like that that we can draw on to build great things

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
like we saw from the previous talk.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
So what I really want to talk about is actually how we get there.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
How do we get R into production?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So maybe you're working at an organization now.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You've perhaps got R on your desktop, something like that.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
But you're not running anything R-based in production.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:30.000
There are traditionally a number of reasons for this.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And they mostly revolve around the way that businesses have evolved

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
in terms of their kind of technology adoption.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And so what we've found when we look at the market

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:51.000
and when we talk to our customers and things like that

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
is that there is interest in adopting new technologies

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:56.000
and bringing new things into the business,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
but they're perhaps not sure how to go about it.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
So this tension, I guess, a lot of people will look at their business

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
and say, well, IT won't let me run R in production.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
But actually, often it's not IT, it's the business as a whole,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
which is obviously what informs IT and kind of provides

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
all the kind of basis for their security infrastructure

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
and the network infrastructure and all that sort of thing.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So there are two kind of distinct approaches that have emerged

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
in the work that I've done and the businesses that we've talked to

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
over the last, so I've been doing this sort of work for about six years.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
There are two paths that I've seen people be really successful with

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
for getting R into their organizations.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And I want to talk a little bit about those now.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:55.000
So the left-hand path is the path of magic, essentially.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:02.000
So if you think about the great talk that we saw a moment ago,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:09.000
part of what happened was that a fantastic shiny app

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
was presented to somebody important, and then that drove

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
the kind of decision-making over whether to use R

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
or something like that downwards in the organization.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So the path of magic is a great path.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
It can be a very short path, but it can also sort of

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
fraught with difficulty, I guess, because what can happen

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
is it can backfire a little bit.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
So this path, I think, is brilliant and, like I say,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.000
can be a really good shortcut, and especially if you've got

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
something really powerful that you can demonstrate.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
But you can get kicked back later on when we come to talk

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
to IT teams about actually getting that stuff

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
into the production ecosystem within the business.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So that's one option, and hopefully that's kind of

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
fairly easy to understand.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
The right-hand path, though, is...

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So the right-hand path has, I guess, I don't want to say

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.000
guarantees, because there are never any guarantees,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
but what you're looking for with the right-hand path

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
is for the business to have confidence in the work

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:24.000
that you're doing.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And historically, that's the area where getting R

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:29.000
into production kind of falls down.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So the IT team might look at the work that a data scientist

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
is doing and go, well, I'm not confident in what you're doing

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
because where's the test team?

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
Where's your requirements document and things like that?

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
All these kind of historical software engineering things

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
that have been sort of adopted by businesses over the last

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
50, 60 years, whatever it may be.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And so we need to kind of address that elephant in the room,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
which is essentially to come to the understanding

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
and to sort of agree that data science isn't software engineering.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
We know it isn't software engineering,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
and that's absolutely fine.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
In terms of the kind of rigor that goes into these

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
different disciplines, the rigor goes into a different place

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.000
in data science.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And so what I usually see from data science teams

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
is that they're very good at ensuring their code does

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.000
what they think it does.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.000
That's obviously extremely important.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:42.000
But also that they're kind of methodologically sound, I guess.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And then data science will often stop there.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
Software engineering, on the other hand,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.000
obviously has a different set of drivers

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
and a different set of goals.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And so software engineering can very quickly mushroom

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
into a much bigger thing where you have things

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
like QA departments and requirements documents

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
and all those sorts of things,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
which you hopefully try and avoid being too onerous

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.000
in the data science world.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So there's this friction between our starting point,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.000
which is the data science,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and then software engineering,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
which is kind of the IT and the business.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So in terms of tackling things head on,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
which is obviously what we're kind of aiming to do,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
and this was just my really quick thoughts,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and there might be different things in your environments,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
but these are some of the things that, as a data scientist,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
you might be pushed into understanding

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
in order to get stuff into production.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
I want to kind of just have a little sidebar on that, though,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
in that I don't think every data scientist

00:10:58.000 --> 00:10:59.000
wants to learn this stuff,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:01.000
and I don't think every data scientist

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
should have to learn this stuff.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
There are a group of data scientists

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.000
who already know this stuff

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
or who are excited by these things,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
but also it's about building bridges with the IT team

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
and getting them to kind of meet you halfway

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:20.000
in these kind of areas.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.000
So you might find that you've got

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
a particularly restrictive IT team

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
who don't want you to run new things in production.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
People are always concerned about new things.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.000
They might break the old things.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.000
They might cause problems.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
There are QA teams that have to be satisfied.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
Who's going to write the test scripts

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.000
and things like that that you might need

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
to take an application from your desktop

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:47.000
to a production environment?

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:49.000
There's automated testing.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:51.000
Joe did a great talk this morning, obviously.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:53.000
It included Shiny load test and Shiny test,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
which are great ways of testing Shiny applications,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
but I can pretty much guarantee

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
that your internal IT team, if you have one,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:05.000
won't be familiar with those tools.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So we need to build those kind of bridges.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Staging servers, integration environments,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
continuous integration, continuous delivery,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.000
these are all concepts

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
that come from that software engineering world

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
rather than from data science,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.000
but they're all the sorts of things

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
that people need to take on board

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
and not necessarily do themselves.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:30.000
Like I say, I genuinely don't think

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
that all data scientists should also be software engineers

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:35.000
in terms of getting things to production,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
but these are the sorts of things that you'll encounter.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
I worked on a project a little while ago.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
My laptop's gone to sleep.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:47.000
I worked on a project a little while ago

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
for a business that wanted to adopt

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
RStudio Connect so that they could deploy

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Shiny applications and things like that,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
and I talked to them initially

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
about how they might go about doing that.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.000
They didn't have any Linux knowledge in-house.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Connect only runs on Linux.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
They didn't have any kind of

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
R administration knowledge in-house,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.000
so they didn't know how they were going to work

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:17.000
things like CRAN and stuff like that,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
and I had a meeting with their security board.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:23.000
They had a board that met every two weeks

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
to discuss any new projects that were coming through

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
from a security perspective,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
and I said to them,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
oh, yeah, it's a programming language like any other.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:36.000
There's not really anything to get excited about,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
and by the way, CRAN's got 13,000 packages on it,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
and they were like, no, it's not going to happen.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
So unfortunately for this customer,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
this was slightly before RStudio's package manager came out,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
so I ended up building them an internal CRAN

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
to get around this very strict requirement that they've got

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
of not bringing 13,000 packages of,

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.000
I don't want to say unchecked code,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.000
but you know what I mean.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
It's kind of community-contributed code

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
into their business.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
So there are a lot of these kind of barriers

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
that will need to be often overcome

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
in these sorts of organizations.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
My background is actually more

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:21.000
on that kind of engineering side.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:23.000
I was an infrastructure support engineer for many years,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.000
and my role now is basically to try and bridge that gap.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So I get into conversations about doing things like,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
well, we'd like an RStudio Connect deployment

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
in our business, and that's great.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
I can do that in half an hour, maybe an hour,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
if it's a complicated installation.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
But then people want all the help around that.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
I can install the tools really, really quickly,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
but most of what I do is actually hearts and minds.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
I write documentation for the Linux team

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
so that the Linux team know how to support R,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
how to compile it from source

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
and where it should be put on the systems

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:06.000
and things like that.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
So it can very quickly mushroom into a thing

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.000
that's got almost nothing to do with data science at all,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
even though it's got everything to do with R.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Production is very much a team sport,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
which is why I talk a lot about building bridges

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.000
between these different disparate groups

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.000
within the organization.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
As I said before, I don't want every data scientist

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
to have to learn all of the kind of software engineering

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
best practice, and I don't think that

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
there are necessarily many data scientists

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
who are interested in that sort of thing,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
which is why it's important to build bridges

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
with these different teams within your organization.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
But obviously in those circumstances,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
it's about building a kind of common language

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
and sort of trying to understand a little bit

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
about what they do.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
So I've put together, and again,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
this list is by no means exhaustive,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
but I've put together a kind of production list

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
or a production readiness checklist

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.000
for some of this stuff.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.000
So when R goes into production,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
you need to think about the target environment.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:18.000
What is the target environment?

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
Is it Windows? Is it Linux?

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
Which versions and things like that?

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
You also need to think about the release process.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:28.000
Can you just take code off your desktop

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
and shove it onto a production server?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Probably not.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So a lot of organizations will have

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:38.000
a formal release process that you'll need

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
to either get on board with

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:43.000
or somehow persuade somebody to adapt

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
for your specific needs.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
You'll probably need a testing strategy,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.000
so it's worth writing down what that is

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
so that when whoever it is from the QA team

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
says, well, you haven't done any testing,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
you can say, well, actually, we've done a lot of testing,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
and our testing strategy is really good and clear.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
Some organizations have a change management process.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
So a really good example for this one

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:09.000
is retail businesses who often don't want

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.000
to change anything in their infrastructure

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.000
over the Christmas period

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
because they're extremely concerned

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.000
that any changes might damage

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
their infrastructure in some way,

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:22.000
and so there'll be a gap, two, three months,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
whatever it is, where literally no changes

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:27.000
can be pushed to production at all.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
You might need a security review.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:30.000
Infrastructure is kind of similar

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.000
to the target environment,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:34.000
but also covers things like,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:36.000
do you need access to databases

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:38.000
and things like that?

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
What is your deployment process?

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Will there be an automated process?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Is it a manual process?

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:46.000
Will you push straight from your desktop?

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:48.000
Is it going to come out of Git or wherever?

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Who's going to support your application?

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:52.000
If you're taking an R application into production,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:54.000
do you want the 3AM support core

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:56.000
when it falls over?

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
Probably not.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Who's going to do the support?

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.000
Are the support team prepared

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:04.000
to support this application?

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.000
Do they have the information they need?

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
With a lot of data science projects,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.000
you do the project and then you move on

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
to the next one, but in production,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.000
we need to think about maintenance.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Who's maintaining this thing

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:18.000
when the initial drop is done?

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Where's version two going to come from?

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:22.000
Who's going to do the bug fixes?

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Who signs off on releases?

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.000
Which version of R are you going to use?

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:28.000
Which packages, which versions?

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:30.000
There's a lot of things to think about.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
This checklist is kind of a starting point.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:34.000
Yours will be different.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Feel free to copy it or take a picture or whatever

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
and add your own things onto that.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.000
These are the kinds of things

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:44.000
that you need to think about.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Once you've done that,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:48.000
you can be happy up a mountain

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
enjoying having R in production.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
The last thing I want to encourage you all to do

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
is if you do have R in production currently

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
or if you do manage to successfully get R

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.000
into production in your organisation,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
I really want you to share

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.000
what you've done somehow, anyway,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:07.000
because it helps lift the rest

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
of the R in production community up.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
It's really good to get these stories out there

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
to encourage others to do the same

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:18.000
and so that we can learn from each other.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
Last thing, that's me,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:23.000
that's the company's website.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
The last thing is the field guide

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.000
to the R ecosystem.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
It has been quite useful

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
for people who don't know R,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:32.000
so people with ops and management backgrounds

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
and things like that.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:36.000
It's a very short, high-level overview

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.000
of the R ecosystem.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:40.000
With that, I will stop talking.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Thank you, Mark.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:51.000
We have time for one question.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
If anybody has any question

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.000
that they would like to pose to Mark,

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.000
we've got microphones.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.000
It looks like we have one right over here.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.000
You mentioned about building

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
an internal CRAN for a company

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
and installing and running unvetted code

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
is kind of a big concern in my organisation.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Were the packages somehow vetted

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
when you were including them

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:17.000
in the repository, or how did that work?

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.000
They were vetted, yes.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
Basically, all I did

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:22.000
was take...

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:24.000
They gave me a list of these

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.000
are the 80 packages that we use.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:28.000
I got those packages from CRAN.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
I got all the dependencies from CRAN.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
I ran their kind of corporate antivirus,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:35.000
their corporate anti-malware stuff

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.000
over those packages,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:39.000
and then I built a small repository

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:41.000
to host them.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.000
That was enough to get

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
their security team on board effectively.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:48.000
Yeah.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:50.000
Thank you.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:52.000
Thank you.

